How many days each week do you get up early, without an alarm, simply because you’re excited to start the day? I shoot for 7 out of 7.

Sometimes it’s adventure on the road, or chasing turtles at home, or often it’s simply waking up to get that first cup of coffee and a workout before the sun makes its appearance. Each day is one that I dictate, not someone else. 

This does not mean that every day turns out as planned. 

There are definitely challenges and disappointments but that means I adjust focus for the next day and am excited to dive head first into that one. Systematically reducing stress, obligation, mental and financial pressure - a little at a time - has netted me enormous benefits. 

It wasn’t always like this. I existed for much of my adult life doing things I hated. Spending Sunday dreading work on Monday. Dragging myself to the office. Watching the clock all day just wishing I was anywhere else. Then the weekend mercifully appeared and I used it to cram in all the personal stuff I ‘didn’t have time for’ during the week. Sunday rolled around again and, yup, repeat cycle. 

Some of it was a means to a worthwhile goal but much of it was just not keeping the right mindset - not realizing I am the only one ultimately in control of my life, as you are with yours. Not your boss, not your family, not the other political party. You. 

Working a job you hate most of the time to maybe do a few you things you enjoy a little of the time isn’t living, it’s dying….and a slow painful death at that. 

If you are not already doing what you love or building a direct route to get there quickly you are short changing yourself. 

Whatever excuses you have remember someone somewhere is doing more with less. 

Consistent incremental action adds up to huge results. Break the mold. Get out there. Get after it.

Meet Bua Noi, Thailand’s only gorilla. She lives alone at the Pata Zoo, commonly referred to as the “The World’s Saddest Zoo”, in a barren cell made of concrete and rusty iron bars on the 7th floor rooftop of a decaying department store in Bangkok. 

Bua Noi was brought here 1987, at the age of 1, after being taken from the wild with 3 other infant gorillas while their mothers were slaughtered for bush meat. 

The average gorilla lives 40 years or so. Bua Noi turns 36 this year. She has no companions or access to natural daylight. A few old tires and a steady procession of interloping rats are her only friends. 

Despite numerous years-long campaigns, protests, and general outrage from within Thailand and around the globe those responsible for holding Bua Noi captive refuse to allow her relocation to a more suitable environment. 

Sadly, although Bua Noi lives in solitary confinement she is not alone at the Pata Zoo. Dozens of other primates share similar misery in their own cells.

I opted to walk the 10 mile round trip to see Bua Nui and the other animals today. I’m grateful I had the choice to do so.

This doesn’t necessarily mean sell all of your stuff and move to Hawaii (although I did and have not looked back…). It’s more about the thoughts and actions of those you spend the most time with. 

Escaping one physical location for another but continuing to associate with Debbie Downers probably won’t fix much. It’s more important that you associate with people who are actually doing what you dream of doing, which in addition to the beautiful beaches and scenery of Hawaii is really what I was looking for. 

What is it that you want to do? Who do you want to become? No goal is too lofty. Whatever it is, find people who are doing exactly that thing - people who take what seems impossible for you as routine for them, and surround yourself with them. 

If you hate your job and are stuck there 60 hours a week with other people who also hate their jobs chances are you will continue moldering away at said job, reinforced by the negativity around you unless you make a deliberate effort to rise above that toxic air for some fresh stuff. 

The “I could never do that…”, “….must be nice…” , “I would love to but…..” crowd has no shortage of reasons why you and they are all victims of chance, held hostage in a world where there is no hope of escape. For them it just does not exist. All for thee and none for me. The excuses in that kind of echo chamber are common and dangerously contagious. 

The best way for some people to numb the pain of their own lack of ambition is to blame circumstance and make others feel trapped with them. We all know misery loves company. To be clear, these acrimonious voices are not necessarily ‘bad’ people - there are tons of wonderful people crippled with debilitating limiting beliefs -  but they are definitely not helping you become your best self. It’s not in their nature, but it can be in yours.

As a fledgling real estate entrepreneur I was indeed surrounded by good people doing good things but I felt I had hit a ceiling on what I could learn from the social and business environment at that time…. (Cont’d in comment section)

National Parks, for the most part, are beautiful. You gotta go see ‘em, take in that beauty, check ‘em off the list.

However, in many cases, the primary experience is not that of solitude and nature and its splendor, but that of traffic jams and throngs of fat people yelling and waving cell phones around while they ignore the antics of their broods of shitty little kids, wreaking immeasurable havoc and generally being horrible people. It’s a nightmare. Nothing draws a crowd like a crowd and that’s what you get. Yellowstone, Zion, Grand Canyon. They’re spectacular places at their cores but get in and get out. And do it as quickly as you can.

With the exception of a short conference in San Diego and a trip home to Maui just long enough to see part of the island tragically burned flat, we’ve been on the road, living in a van, for 3 months now.

10 out of 10 times so far I’ll take the anonymous random state or national forests that nobody outside of the immediate area they are located in has ever heard of. No hours of operation, fees to be paid, or reservations needed. No check in or check out times, rules, tags, registration, bathroom codes, and certainly no Groupon specials for you and the entire extended family. 

Across Oregon, Nevada, Utah, Colorado, Wyoming and now Montana these off-the-grid camping areas have hands down been my favorite. Take this place we’re at now, somewhere in Eastern Montana. I read the name of the park on the map a couple days ago but forgot it as soon as we rolled in. I couldn’t tell you what city or what county we’re in and I’ll never remember enough to tell anyone how to get here. I don’t care. 

What I do care about is I was able to hike what has become a fairly standard 2 hours this morning without so much as seeing another human. I’ll do it again this evening. And probably tomorrow too. Just me and a bunch of prairie dogs out in the middle of nowhere. We could be 10 or a 1000 miles from civilization. Doesn’t matter. It’s incredible. This spot won’t make anyone’s list of “must see” places nor will any of my other highlights over the past summer, and that’s perfectly fine with me.

Since the Kingdom of Hawaii forbids its commoners from registering vehicles that are not physically located anywhere on the islands it effectively prohibits us from owning vehicles on the mainland. 

Brilliant policy, since in this case it would have netted Maui County a 5-figure check for a vehicle that would never touch their streets.

After a total shitshow of pursuing alternatives, including logging over 8,000 miles across 14 states in 5 months with no license plate or valid registration, today I announce my return to compliance with the law. 

I would like to thank all of my accomplices. They will remain unnamed for their own protection. 

I’m thrilled to finally have a plate, even if it does have a side profile of Joe Biden on it. Way less stressful driving now, although, I feel I’m qualified to teach a Master Class on “How to Quickly Evade a Cop Without Making it Obvious You Are Quickly Evading a Cop”.

Ever since the days back in the ‘80’s watching Robert Stack narrate those “Unsolved Mysteries’ segments on aliens I’ve been hooked on UFO’s.

Visiting Roswell today, even though it may now primarily be a campy tourist trap, was a lot of fun.

With the recent wild testimonies from highly respectable people like David Fravor, David Grusch, James Lacatski, and others regarding the US government’s programs on tracking and even recovering alien spacecraft (including “non-human biologics”…) plus the unwavering stories of reverse engineering actual recovered alien craft from the GOAT (or Greatest of All Nutcases?) Bob Lazar it seems if there is a truth to any of this the pace is picking up as to when we might actually see it.

One interesting comment that David Grusch made on his recent JRE Podcast appearance is that the government may be withholding UFO info not only to prevent the upheaval of society as we know it, but to avoid massive lawsuits from defense and other contractors who may have been bypassed in what would normally be an opportunity for them to bid on this cutting edge and potentially massively profitable work. The ramifications could result in billions and billions of dollars in judgements. The latter reason actually seems more plausible to me than the former, but who knows. 

I think a little more transparency around intelliegent life from beyond our planet visiting us, if it really is happening, could potentially be a catalyst to unite us warring morons here on earth. 

In the meantime, I’ll continue to stare at the night sky and wonder. 

Maybe it was just a weather balloon that crashed in Roswell. Yeah, maybe.

What do you think?

Living in a van down by the…Sea of Cortez. 🐬🐠🐳🌅

We rolled off the dealer lot in California thinking we’d explore in our new van for a couple weeks at a time, store it wherever we got bored, fly back to Maui, and then fly back to the van when we were ready to go again. ✈️

That was 6 months, 20 states, 2 countries, and 15,000 miles ago. 🗺️

We’ve done a few simple things to help ensure stability and long term viability thus far.

Internet. With Starlink we can be connected anywhere at anytime, seamlessly. Being on the road doesn’t have to mean totally checking out and abandoning all real world responsibilities (although if you are able to do that more power to you). A cubicle and the entire work day feels a lot nicer on the beach and with a new view every day or so. 💻

Diet. With an onboard kitchen & fridge we can keep our eating habits healthy and controlled. 🥩🥔

Exercise. A $25/mo Planet Fitness membership has allowed the luxury of gym workouts and real showers multiple times per week. Combined with an assortment of mobile fitness equipment like kettlebells, a TRX, and fitness bands in the van when we’re really far off the grid have helped keep exercise goals on track. 🏋️‍♂️

Not sure how long we’ll keep this going but at the 6 month mark I feel like we’re just getting warmed up. 🔥🔥
